{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_28","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,220p' papers/README.md\"","aggregated_output":"# Downloaded Papers\n\nThis directory contains 16 downloaded PDFs plus chunked page ranges for priority papers in `papers/pages/`.\n\n1. **Can LLMs Generate Novel Research Ideas? A Large-Scale Human Study with 100+ NLP Researchers**\n   - File: `2409.04109_llm_research_ideas_human_study.pdf`\n   - Authors: Chenglei Si, Diyi Yang, Tatsunori Hashimoto\n   - Year: 2024\n   - Source: https://arxiv.org/abs/2409.04109\n   - Why relevant: controlled expert comparison of human and LLM-generated NLP research ideas; reports higher judged novelty for LLM ideas but weaker feasibility and diversity issues.\n\n2. **SciMON: Scientific Inspiration Machines Optimized for Novelty**\n   - File: `2305.14259_scimon.pdf`\n   - Authors: Qingyun Wang, Doug Downey, Heng Ji, Tom Hope\n   - Year: 2023/2024\n   - Source: https://arxiv.org/abs/2305.14259\n   - Why relevant: explicit literature-grounded novelty optimization via inspiration retrieval and iterative comparison to prior work.\n\n3. **ResearchAgent: Iterative Research Idea Generation over Scientific Literature with Large Language Models**\n   - File: `2404.07738_researchagent.pdf`\n   - Authors: Jinheon Baek, Sujay Kumar Jauhar, Silviu Cucerzan, Sung Ju Hwang\n   - Year: 2024/2025\n   - Source: https://arxiv.org/abs/2404.07738\n   - Why relevant: generates problems, methods, and experiment designs from a core paper, academic graph references, entity retrieval, and reviewing-agent feedback.\n\n4. **SciPIP: An LLM-based Scientific Paper Idea Proposer**\n   - File: `2410.23166_scipip.pdf`\n   - Authors: Wenxiao Wang et al.\n   - Year: 2024/2025\n   - Source: https://arxiv.org/abs/2410.23166\n   - Why relevant: improves ideation with semantic/citation/full-text literature retrieval and a dual-path generation framework.\n\n5. **Chain of Ideas: Revolutionizing Research Via Novel Idea Development with LLM Agents**\n   - File: `2410.13185_chain_of_ideas.pdf`\n   - Authors: Long Li et al.\n   - Year: 2024/2025\n   - Source: https://arxiv.org/abs/2410.13185\n   - Why relevant: organizes literature into forward/backward development chains and uses novelty-checking refinement.\n\n6. **The AI Scientist: Towards Fully Automated Open-Ended Scientific Discovery**\n   - File: `2408.06292_ai_scientist.pdf`\n   - Authors: Chris Lu et al.\n   - Year: 2024\n   - Source: https://arxiv.org/abs/2408.06292\n   - Why relevant: end-to-end system for ideation, coding, experiments, paper writing, and automated review; useful baseline for proposal/execution grounding.\n\n7. **Is this Idea Novel? An Automated Benchmark for Judgment of Research Ideas**\n   - File: `2603.10303_rinobench.pdf`\n   - Authors: Tim Schopf, Michael Farber\n   - Year: 2026\n   - Source: https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.10303\n   - Why relevant: RINoBench provides expert-derived novelty labels, related works, and metrics for judging idea novelty.\n\n8. **Literature-Grounded Novelty Assessment of Scientific Ideas**\n   - File: `2506.22026_literature_grounded_novelty_assessment.pdf`\n   - Authors: Simra Shahid et al.\n   - Year: 2025\n   - Source: https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.22026\n   - Why relevant: RAG novelty checker with keyword/snippet retrieval, embedding filtering, facet reranking, and expert examples.\n\n9. **IdeaBench: Benchmarking Large Language Models for Research Idea Generation**\n   - File: `2411.02429_ideabench.pdf`\n   - Authors: Sikun Guo et al.\n   - Year: 2024\n   - Source: https://arxiv.org/abs/2411.02429\n   - Why relevant: dataset and Insight Score framework for low/high-resource research idea generation from references.\n\n10. **AI Idea Bench 2025: AI Research Idea Generation Benchmark**\n    - File: `2504.14191_ai_idea_bench_2025.pdf`\n    - Authors: Yansheng Qiu et al.\n    - Year: 2025\n    - Source: https://arxiv.org/abs/2504.14191\n    - Why relevant: 3,495 AI target papers with motivating papers and evaluation against ground-truth paper content/reference material.\n\n11. **Evaluating LLMs' Divergent Thinking Capabilities for Scientific Idea Generation with Minimal Context**\n    - File: `2412.17596_liveideabench.pdf`\n    - Authors: Kai Ruan et al.\n    - Year: 2024/2026\n    - Source: https://arxiv.org/abs/2412.17596\n    - Why relevant: LiveIdeaBench evaluates scientific creativity from single-keyword prompts across originality, feasibility, fluency, flexibility, and clarity.\n\n12. **NovBench: Evaluating Large Language Models on Academic Paper Novelty Assessment**\n    - File: `2604.11543_novbench.pdf`\n    - Authors: Wenqing Wu et al.\n    - Year: 2026\n    - Source: https://arxiv.org/abs/2604.11543\n    - Why relevant: benchmark for novelty assessment text using paper-review pairs and relevance/correctness/coverage/clarity metrics.\n\n13. **MLAgentBench: Evaluating Language Agents on Machine Learning Experimentation**\n    - File: `2310.03302_mlagentbench.pdf`\n    - Authors: Qian Huang, Jian Vora, Percy Liang, Jure Leskovec\n    - Year: 2023/2024\n    - Source: https://arxiv.org/abs/2310.03302\n    - Why relevant: benchmark for executable ML experimentation by agents; useful for the small-experiment grounding arm.\n\n14. **DiscoveryBench: Towards Data-Driven Discovery with Large Language Models**\n    - File: `2407.01725_discoverybench.pdf`\n    - Authors: Bodhisattwa Prasad Majumder et al.\n    - Year: 2024/2025\n    - Source: https://arxiv.org/abs/2407.01725\n    - Why relevant: data-driven discovery tasks requiring statistical analysis and semantic reasoning.\n\n15. **ScienceAgentBench: Toward Rigorous Assessment of Language Agents for Data-Driven Scientific Discovery**\n    - File: `2410.05080_scienceagentbench.pdf`\n    - Authors: Ziru Chen et al.\n    - Year: 2024/2025\n    - Source: https://arxiv.org/abs/2410.05080\n    - Why relevant: 102 expert-validated data-driven scientific coding tasks from 44 papers.\n\n16. **Improving Scientific Hypothesis Generation with Knowledge Grounded Large Language Models**\n    - File: `2411.02382_kg_coi_hypothesis_generation.pdf`\n    - Authors: Guangzhi Xiong et al.\n    - Year: 2024\n    - Source: https://arxiv.org/abs/2411.02382\n    - Why relevant: knowledge-graph-grounded chain-of-ideas approach for reducing hallucination in hypothesis generation.\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
